„Yes, Captain. They should be on their way by now, they were still in the mess hall to collect their rations.“         At exactly 0500, the Exodus Company gathered at the vehicle park. Shaw climbed onto a box and began to speak.
“We will be relocated to the forward deployment site I-131, fifty miles outside Ianlos. Our task is to support the ongoing siege and the later attack on Ianlos to drive out the rebels. We will establish a base camp at the foot of the mountains there,” explained Shaw. “March to your squads and mount up.”
The company broke into their respective squads, and the soldiers were distributed among the tanks by the non-commissioned officers. Cohren climbed into one of the tanks further up in the convoy, where he met Nemic, Craith, and two new recruits. Cohren remembered their arrival a few days ago but knew little about them. He sat sideways and swung his legs while adjusting his backpack and the radio equipment, which was connected to his headphones and throat microphone.
“Hey Cohren, is Snowball still with Harris?” asked Nemic after they had settled in.
“Do you mean the rooster he stole?” Cohren recalled the morning when they let the animal go on a farmer's field. “Yes, I think so.”
Cohren looked over to one of the other tanks and spotted Harris with his squad. Out of the corner of his eye, he could see the movement of a small rooster, constantly turning its head to search the surroundings.
“Yes, he’s still with him,” replied Cohren as the hatch of the tank opened and the commander came into view.
“All tanks advance,” the commander spoke slowly and calmly into his headset. The engines of the column of tanks and Strikers roared to life as they started moving. The Kronos tank, which Cohren was riding in, shook as the brakes were released and they fell into formation. The tanks moved in a wedge formation across the Itania Plain. Despite the winter storms, the swamp areas were frozen and the forests were snow-covered, yet the mud was everywhere.
About an hour later, one of the recruits, whom Cohren knew was named Orson, started speaking. “Lieutenant, you’ve been here since the start of the war, right?”
“Yes, Operation Firestorm,” replied Cohren. “We thought it would be wrapped up in a few weeks, but we underestimated them.”
„Underestimated is severely understatements,“ Nemic interrupted the conversation. „We were not prepared for their arsenal and the mass of soldiers. In the first two weeks, they destroyed the UFS Revenant, and only last month the Erebus. We should even see them on our way.“
„I stand firmly by the side of the Federation,“ Orson declared defiantly. „I won't let these terrorists scare me.“
„You say that now,“ Craith explained. „But I've seen that most of the eighteen-year-old recruits like you usually take cover as soon as they hear a shot.“
„We'll see,“ Cohren said laughing. Orson ended the conversation.
„Exodus XO, Exodus CO,“ Cohren's radio crackled. „We're receiving thermal signatures, around 300 meters away, 20 degrees to the right.“
Cohren climbed up onto the tank and put on his special infrared goggles. When he switched them to "thermal image," he could see the signatures in the distance.
„Yes, I see them,“ Cohren replied into his throat microphone.
„Are they hostile?“ another recruit, Natayla, asked.
„Can't tell yet,“ Cohren answered. He grabbed his microphone and said: „Exodus Company, engage only if engaged. We'll draw them out.“
As they approached, the dot-like thermal signatures began to take shape. As they got closer, one of them suddenly ran off hastily to retrieve something. She immediately returned to the small hill where the others were, and the figures lay down, taking shooting positions.
„We have enemy contact,“ Shaw called over the radio as orange tracer rounds were fired from the hilltop. While the tanks were under fire, the infantry leaped out and took cover. A rocket flew past and exploded behind the formation, scattering debris and rubble onto one of the tanks. Another rocket hit a Stryker, an APS-Cerberus, and exploded. The crew quickly climbed out and took cover as the ammunition detonated into the air.
„Iron 1-2 and 1-3, 25 degrees right, 300 meters. Fire,“ the armored column's commander shouted over the radio. Iron 1-2 and 1-3 opened fire, grenades flying towards the hill and exploding, sending dirt and stone into the air.
„Send the Sentis in,“ Knoxx called, observing the hill with a telescope. The rear hatch of a Cerberus opened and an unarmed soldier emerged, wearing a special headset. He gave commands into a square microphone, and two Sentis, officially called Sentinels, charged out. With their thin, metallic limbs swinging forward, they sprinted. They carried their weapons on their backs.
„Kill or capture?“ Craith asked as they watched.
„Looks like capture,“ Cohren guessed, as the two Sentinels disappeared into the cloud of ash and smoke. Screams and gunshots echoed from the hill but quickly faded. Shortly thereafter, the two Sentinels returned and dragged someone behind them, leaving footprints in the ground. After retreating to the cover of the column, they threw the figure onto the ground. The figure groaned in pain as it landed hard in the mud and snow.
Shaw went to the figure that was just trying to stand up. Then he turned to one of the Sentinels. "How many?"
"Three dead, sir," the Sentinel answered. "The rest fled on foot."
Shaw nodded and turned to Cohren and Craith, who were standing nearby. "Get this guy out of my sight!"
